1. Summary

The health-focused global smart device market has been booming for over eight years, and the market projection is to reach almost 25 billion by 2025. The smart devices categories include diagnostics, monitoring, and therapeutic, and some of the key players in the market are Fitbit and Apple. Fitbit has contributed to the accelerated growth of smart devices through partnerships which includes their health screening and monitoring app, FibriCheck. For instance, users in European countries like Germany and France can monitor their heart rhythm for abnormalities with their Fitbit smart watch. In addition, Amazon has recently joined the race by launching a fitness tracker that can track fat mass and even the person’s emotions.

The case study utilizes data from Fitbit to analyze the Bellabeat app, which allows users to track health data in terms of fitness, sleep, menstrual cycle, and mindfulness habits. Analyzing Fitbit users’ data will provide insights on the usage of smart tracking devices. These questions will guide the analysis:

  1. What are some trends in smart device usage?
  2. How could these trends apply to Bellabeat customers?
  3. How could these trends help influence Bellabeat marketing strategy?

Approach:

An exploratory approach will guide the analysis with a series of questions, trends, and regression analyses. The idea is to explore users’ habits based on their tracker. Thirty eligible Fitbit users provided their consent to use their data. Their answers will aid in exploring their activity tracking in the app.

Fitness trackers such as Bellabeat or Fitbit provide information into users’ routines and device usage, which can illuminate marketing campaign objectives. Therefore, the purpose of the below questions is to take a deeper dive into the analysis:

  1. Which features of the app can help users track their activity?
  2. How are users tracking their weight in the app and connected devices such as scales?

Daily data tracked for physical activity, and weight measurements levels are part of the analysis.

Disclaimer: All the data is research-based only.

2. Introduction

Bellabeat Wellness Coach App

Plot this way

App Description:

Bellabeat app is a repository for all Bellabeat devices and products such as:

  • Leaf
  • Wellness tracker
  • Spring
  • Smart water bottle
  • Time, a hybrid wellness watch

The app ” is a combination of a holistic wellness coach and tracker designed for women.” - Bellabeat.

App Features:

  • Personalized coaching programs
  • App releases monthly enhanced programs
  • App reads and transforms information such as sleep and activity tracking and breathing exercises captured by Bellabeat devices. The processed information becomes usable fitness and wellness data
  • App motivational notifications feature encourages users

Fitbit App

Plot this way

App Description:

The Fitbit app is a customizable software that allows users to understand their statistical data and fitness progress better. The app provides insightful information for the user to reach fitness goals and objectives, “Meet the app that puts a world of health & fitness in your hands. -fitbit.com

App Features:

  • Adaptable workouts tailored to the user
  • App tracks active minutes, number of steps and distance, calories burned, sleep, heart rate
  • User’s daily and over time progress in terms of nutrition and weight
  • App offers a motivation & friends feature to connect with other users, join groups and participate in challenges

Fitbit Data

Data downloaded from click here! from the Kaggle web repository.

Fitbit fitness tracker data is part of Kaggle’s public data sets available through Mobius. As stated on Kaggle’s page, thirty eligible Fitbit users consented to submit and provide their tracker data in a survey via Amazon Mechanical Turk between March 12, 2016, to May 12, 2016. However, sample size and nonexistent demographic and geographic data limit the scope of this analysis.

CSV Files

CSV Files Included for the analysis: Daily Activity, Daily Steps, Weight Log

Data files click here!

Raw data files were downloaded to local machine and imported into to RStudio as data frames with shorter names for better manipulation.

daily_activity <-read.csv(“dailyActivity_merged.csv”) weight_log <- read.csv(“weightLogInfo_merged.csv”) daily_steps <- read.csv(“dailySteps_merged.csv”)

Data Cleaning and Transformation

packages installed for data cleaning: “here”, “skimr”, “janitor”, “dplyr”

The datasets daily_activity,and daily_steps did not contain any missing values, but the weight_log data set had 65 missing values as verified with the sum(is.na(df)) function for finding missing values. For this analysis, we will use the na.exclude function to drop the rows with the missing data, but the na.exclude function allows keeping track of where the missing values were. Therefore, when running different statistical analyses the vector will retain the length of the original response.

  geom_point() + geom_smooth() +
  labs(title = "Total Steps vs. Light Active Distance")+
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5))
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'

In the Total Steps vs. Very Active Distance graph, most of the data points are below the 10000 steps mark, but the graph trends upward, indicating that as Total Steps increase, the very active distance increases slowly at first and then more rapidly. On the contrary, for the TotalSteps vs. LightActiveDistance graph, the data points cluster around 10000-15000 steps, but the graph plateaus right after the 10000 steps, which could indicate that as the number of total steps increases, the distance increases rapidly at first and then the activity increment slows down significantly.

par(mfrow=c(1,2))
hist(daily_activity$VeryActiveMinutes, co = "darkred", main = "Very Active", xlab = "Very Active Minutes", breaks = 7)
hist(daily_activity$LightlyActiveMinutes, co ="darkblue", main = "Lightly Active", xlab = "Lightly Active Minutes", breaks = 10)

The frequency for the ‘Very Active Minutes’ red graph is remarkably higher than the lightly active minutes. The distribution for the very active minutes is positively skewed, and most data falls to the right. Most active minutes range (0 - 50) with a frequency of 800 instances, followed by a (50-100) interval with only 100 instances. The highest interval reported was (200-250) but with only one occurrence.

The blue ‘Lightly Active Minutes’ graph has more instances with intervals between 0 and 50, 50 and 100. The most significant frequency of lightly active minutes recorded was in the 200 and 250 range or time intervals with a longer tail to the right than to the left. There is also a minor hill whose peak is at the 0-50 minute range.

The box plots for the minute activity levels indicate that the main bulk of the data was below 50 and the maximum very active minutes were below 100, but the number of outliers starts below the 100 mark. For the ‘Fairly Active Minutes’ graph, the bulk of the data is between the median and the upper quartile = 20. The upper extreme is around the 50 mark, followed by multiple outliers. Both graphs, ‘Very Active’ and ‘Fairly Active Minutes,’ are right-skewed, with no lower extreme points but 0 as the lower quartile for both box plots.

The lightly active minutes have a more symmetrical distribution with 0 as the lower extreme, 200 as the median, and right below 500 as the upper extreme with five outliers. An extreme of 0 lower-quartile is not surprising for the sedentary minutes and a median above 1000. The upper extreme was 1400, but with an absence of outliers.

grid.arrange(p1, p2, p3)

The variable TotalSteps was converted to miles assuming that, on average, there are about 32 inches per step and 63,360 inches in a mile, then dividing 63,360 by 32, which equals 1980 Miles. Dividing the mean number of steps 7638 by 1980 gives us approximately 4/4.5 miles. The mean distance for the variable TotalDistance is around 5 miles which is the mileage recorded in the TrackerDistance variable.

## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

Seven participants recorded the 67 observations for weight as per the grouping coloring based on participant Id. As is usually the case, weight and BMI indicate a positive linear relationship: as weight goes up, so does BMI. The magnitude of the correlation is r = 0.53, which indicates that the two variables are moderately correlated, and the p-value = 0.000000000001329 indicates a statistically significant correlation based on a significance threshold set at .05. The BMI coefficients indicate that, on average, weight went up by 0.073 units pounds as BMI increased.

For the BMI ~ Fat correlation, 65 rows containing missing values were removed, and only values for two valid IDs were captured. Therefore, the sample size was insufficient to have a valid model. Nevertheless, from the two recorded data, the trend seemed to capture a positive relationship between BMI and fat. The coefficient indicated that, on average, fat would increase by 1.60 units as BMI went up. BMI levels below 25 are ideal. The two data points recorded for BMI are close to or above the 25 mark.

The pie chart indicates the proportion of information for automatically detected and manually entered weights. According to the ‘Fitabase” data dictionary, the variable IsManualReport is a Boolean data type that captures users’ weigh-in activities. The 26 frequencies marked as TRUE are the weigh-in users who have entered or logged in manually, whereas the remaining 41 marked as FALSE are weigh-ins measured and synchronized directly to Fitbit.com from a connected scale. See link. In the ‘Fitabase’ data dictionary, the manual refers to user-specified activity logs and can override some or all tracker data. There were 61% manual weigh-in recordings and 39% weigh-ins directly measured by a Fitbit connected scale.

The SedentaryMinutes ~ TotalDistance correlation indicated a negative linear relationship: as sedentary minutes go up, the total distance of activity goes down. The 490 observations indicated a correlation magnitude of r = 0.82, which signals a strong inverse correlation between the two variables with a statistically significant p-value: < 0.00000000000000022. The SedentaryMinutes coefficient indicates that, on average, as sedentary time increases, total distance decreases by 22.11 steps heterogeneously across the participants.

Findings and Opportunities

Plot this way

Trends in Smart Device Usage

  1. Users recorded their daily fitness and activity levels as VeryActiveDistance, ModeratelyActiveDistance, LightActiveDistance, and SedentaryActiveDistance. The average for the VeryActiveDistance category was much lower than the LightActiveDistance category, with 1.503 and 3.341 miles, respectively.
  2. Sedentary minutes had a higher number of track records as opposed to very active or fairly active minutes, 
  3. The mean total steps recorded was 7638, which is below the General Surgeon’s recommendation of 10000 daily steps.
  4. There were only 67 weight records from seven participants and only two records for fat levels. Additionally, 61% of manual weigh-in recordings and 39% of weigh-ins were directly measured by a Fitbit connected scale.

Fitbit Trends and Bellabeat Customers

  1. Data recorded from light to very active levels provides an opportunity to incentivize device and app users based on their level of activity with a reward system that encourages them to track their data as much as possible. Periods of very active distance are when users recorded their highest distance. Nevertheless, ActiveLightDistance had a higher mean than VeryActiveDistance. Motivation messages in the app could encourage users to increase their activity levels and improve their fitness scores.
  2. Break down activities, so that time devoted to non-strenuous activities such as gardening or housework gets recorded with calories burnt during those periods and accounted for in the tracker.
  3. Create friendly and inspirational reminders for users to complete the ideal 10000 daily steps
  4. The low levels in weight and fat records can be an indication that participants probably hesitated or forgot to record that information; this is where features such as connected scales could play an essential role in recording the information automatically for the user.

Marketing Strategy Recommendations

  • Offer at-home personalized online training and workouts tailored to the needs of users
  • Get more involved with clients by connecting and suggesting effective workouts that speak to their fitness struggles and fitness goals
  • Share trainers’ stories about their workout journey, and incentivize users to share their fitness journeys and success stories through a free channel
  • Concentrate more efforts to understand better how users are interacting with the app and use the data to deliver curated experiences
  • Becoming more data-driven will allow the company to leverage tools to use behavioral data to improve customization, messaging, and dialogue with users about their fitness journeys
  • Strengthen the app towards a more integrated repository that provides a more holistic view of health, biological cycles, and their relationship with fitness and well-being. The idea is that the user find a connection between the great benefits of an integrated tracker and their well-being
  • A connected app to an electronic scale can help users keep more accurate records and stay focused on their fitness goals
